   "source": [
    "#### 9) Discussion points\n",
    "1) How did the scaffolds and functional groups perform in the model performance in comparison the molecular descriptors? Comment on possible reasons. Which combination was suited best?\n",
    "- **Molecular descriptors (X_md) performed best (R² = 0.619).** Scaffolds alone (R² = 0.207) and functional groups alone (R² = 0.065) were much weaker, as OHE scaffolds are very sparse and functional groups only provide 9 binary features. Adding them to descriptors even slightly hurt performance (0.614), likely because the sparse columns introduced noise. X_md alone is therefore the best feature set.\n",
    "2) Is the One-Hot Encoding needed in this case?\n",
    "- For **functional groups** no, since they are already binary (0/1), so OHE adds nothing extra. A simple binary matrix is sufficient.\n",
    "\n",
    "- For **scaffolds** yes, OHE is needed because scaffolds are categorical strings (e.g. `\"c1ccccc1\"`), which a Random Forest cannot handle directly. OHE converts them into a numeric format the model can work with.\n",
    "3) Did the feature filtering (variance, correlation) have an improving effect? Explain!\n",
    "- Feature pruning reduced the dimensionality by 31 % 67 features removed → model got simpler,\n",
    "- R^2 remained nearly unchanged (0.619 → 0.620) → those features added nothing. This proves the removed features were redundant or uninformative\n",
    "- A simpler model with fewer features is always preferred and easier to interpret, faster to train, less risk of overfitting on new molecules.\n",
    "\n",
    "4) Consider to make this kind of workflow for feature comparison more generally usable: How would a clean solution look? How could you ensure compatibility with other models? How would the function / pipeline look schematically?\n",
    "- I would use a pipeline with the following: SMILES → Feature Extraction → Feature Selection → Model → R² score. Compatibility with other models is ensured because all sklearn models share the same .fit()/.predict() interface, you simply swap the last step of the pipeline.\n",
    "5) Visualisation: Using the scaffold fingerprints and the fingerprints for the entire molecule makes a huge difference. What is reason for this effect? Discuss this approach in contrast to similarity thresholds in the Butina clustering.\n",
    "- **Full molecule fingerprints** encode the entire structure including side chains → molecules that share a scaffold but have different substituents appear far apart → many small tight clusters, most molecules unclustered (big blue part in Task 7).\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Scaffold fingerprints** strip away side chains → many molecules that were different now map to the same point → far fewer unique fingerprints, much more spread out UMAP, almost every point gets a cluster colour.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Butina cutoff:** Butina uses a similarity threshold to define clusters, you control granularity via the cutoff. Scaffold fingerprints achieve a similar \"coarsening\" effect automatically by removing side chain information, without needing to tune the cutoff.\n",
    "6) When might scaffolding prove useful?\n",
    "- If you want to synthesize or discover molecules which have the same basis in the core and differ only in the side chains. (used in drug discovery)\n",
    "7) Is toxicity correlated to molecular structure? I.e. what did the toxicity map in UMAP space reveal?\n",
    "- Yes, toxicity is correlated to molecular structure. Structurally similar molecules (same UMAP region) tend to share similar toxicity values, visible as colour gradients in the plot. However, the dataset is dominated by highly toxic compounds (mostly red/orange, low LD50), with only a few isolated clusters showing low toxicity (yellow/green), indicating limited chemical diversity in the low-toxicity space.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "371ab5a0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Answers\n",
    "1. X_md performed best (R2 = 0.618). X_md_scaf and X_md_scaf_fg were slightly worse, while X_scaf (0.208) and X_fg (0.026) were much weaker. Probably becasue X_md has the most complete describtion of the molecules. X_scaf is too course and X_fg is very sparce and simple\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Yes for scaffolds and functional groups in the regression task, because they are categorical. For Morgan fingerprints, no one-hot encoding is needed tho\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Yes, but only slightly: pruning improved X_md from 0.6178 to 0.6238 after removing 24 low-variance and 39 highly correlated features.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. A clean solution would be a reusable pipeline: feature generation -> optional filtering -> model training -> evaluation, with the same split and metric for every feature set.\n",
    "\n",
    "5. Full-molecule fingerprints gave many more, smaller clusters, while scaffold fingerprints gave fewer, much larger clusters. The scaffold representation removes side-chain detail, so molecules look more similar and cluster together more easily.\n",
    "\n",
    "6. Scaffolding is useful when you want to study chemotypes, shared cores, or structure families instead of fine structural differences.\n",
    "\n",
    "7. Toxicity appears only weakly correlated with structure: there may be local trends in UMAP space, but no strong global separation.\n"
   ]
  },
